pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
No scheduled payments yet

Set one up and your recurring payments — bills, subscriptions, transfers — run on the dates you choose, without having to come back and trigger them manually. You stay in control of the schedule; the payments just happen.

Schedule a payment

DRAFT B (generic):
Nothing scheduled yet

Set up a payment once and let it run on its own schedule — no reminders needed, no due dates to chase. Whether it's a recurring bill or a regular transfer, scheduled payments handle the timing for you.

You stay in control and can adjust or cancel anytime.

Schedule a Payment

DRAFT C (original preference):
No scheduled payments yet

Set up a scheduled payment and it'll show up here — so you always know what's coming and when.

Schedule a Payment

RUBRIC CRITERIA (the user's personalized writing quality criteria):
{
  "rubric": [
    {
      "name": "Functional completeness",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "Every standalone piece of copy does its full job without depending on another element to close the loop. Messages name the problem, provide relevant context, and point to the next action \u2014 all within the same unit. A user who sees only that one element should have enough to act.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "names_the_problem",
          "label": "Clearly states what happened or went wrong"
        },
        {
          "id": "provides_context",
          "label": "Gives enough 'why' for the user to understand the situation without guessing"
        },
        {
          "id": "points_to_action",
          "label": "Includes a clear next step or direction within the same element"
        },
        {
          "id": "standalone_sufficient",
          "label": "Element makes sense and feels complete if the user never sees the next screen"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 1
    },
    {
      "name": "User-centered direction",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "The user is the subject of the copy, not the product or the situation. Copy puts the user in motion \u2014 they are the one acting, finding, fixing \u2014 rather than watching the product assess or narrate. CTAs tell the user exactly what will happen when they click. Second person, present tense by default.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "user_as_subject",
          "label": "The user is positioned as the agent doing the action, not the product"
        },
        {
          "id": "cta_specificity",
          "label": "Buttons and links describe the outcome of clicking, not vague verbs like 'try again' or 'submit'"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_blame",
          "label": "Nothing in the copy implies the user made a mistake or did something wrong"
        },
        {
          "id": "forward_momentum",
          "label": "Copy orients toward the next action rather than dwelling on or explaining the current state"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Trust through specificity",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "Reassurance is earned by naming concrete realities the user cares about \u2014 saved progress, nothing charged, specific causes \u2014 not by using reassurance language ('don't worry,' 'no problem'). Confidence comes from being specific, not from telling the user to feel confident. No hedging and no overclaiming.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "concrete_reassurance",
          "label": "Reassuring statements reference specific, verifiable facts rather than emotional soothing"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_hedging",
          "label": "Avoids 'probably,' 'likely,' 'might,' or other language that undercuts the copy's own confidence"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_overclaiming",
          "label": "Does not promise outcomes the product cannot guarantee"
        },
        {
          "id": "addresses_silent_anxieties",
          "label": "Proactively resolves concerns the user would have but might not articulate (e.g., 'was I charged?' 'did I lose my cart?')"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Economy and precision",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "Every word does specific, identifiable work. No throat-clearing, no filler, no over-introducing self-explanatory elements. Copy is short and scannable. If a list has clear labels and descriptions, the line above it doesn't need to explain what the list is.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "no_throat_clearing",
          "label": "No setup lines, preambles, or transition phrases that delay the useful content"
        },
        {
          "id": "every_word_earns_place",
          "label": "Removing any word would change or lose the meaning"
        },
        {
          "id": "scannable",
          "label": "Structure supports quick visual parsing \u2014 short sentences, clear hierarchy, labeled sections"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_redundant_framing",
          "label": "Does not introduce or describe elements that are already self-explanatory from their content"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Tonal calibration",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Copy hits a precise register: calm and grounded without being clinical, warm without being breezy, confident without cheerleading. The target is 'the copy equivalent of a calm nod' \u2014 the way a competent colleague would talk to you after a snag. No pep talks, no customer-service voice, no sardonic edge, no shrugging.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "no_cheerleading",
          "label": "Avoids pep-talk language, forced optimism, or performative warmth"
        },
        {
          "id": "not_clinical",
          "label": "Does not read like a system log, support article, or procedure document"
        },
        {
          "id": "calm_not_breezy",
          "label": "Reads as grounded and steady rather than casual or dismissive"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_sardonic_edge",
          "label": "Never anticipates negative user behavior or introduces anxiety that wasn't already there"
        },
        {
          "id": "human_register",
          "label": "Sounds like something a real person would actually say \u2014 plain, direct, conversational without performing conversational"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    },
    {
      "name": "Contextual presence",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "Copy feels written for the specific screen, moment, and emotional state the user is in \u2014 not lifted from a generic pattern library. It should be clear from the copy alone what just happened, without the copy explicitly narrating or commenting on the situation. The line should feel like it knows where the user is.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "moment_specific",
          "label": "Copy would feel out of place on a different screen or in a different context"
        },
        {
          "id": "answers_real_question",
          "label": "Addresses the question the user is silently asking, not an adjacent or assumed question"
        },
        {
          "id": "not_narrating",
          "label": "Acknowledges the situation without describing or commenting on it from the outside"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_editorializing",
          "label": "Does not comment on the difficulty, commonality, or expected duration of the situation"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 6
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "UX/product copy (error states, recovery flows, and transactional screens)",
  "user_goals_summary": "Writes interface copy that feels like a calm, competent presence alongside the user \u2014 not narrating their situation from above, not performing empathy, just plainly and precisely meeting them where they are. Every word must do specific work for the specific moment it appears in, and the user should always feel like the subject of the copy, never the object of it.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user has an extraordinarily fine-grained sense of tonal register \u2014 they can distinguish between 'calm' and 'breezy,' between 'confident' and 'cheerleading,' between 'present' and 'narrating.' Expect many rounds of iteration on tone, especially on transitional or introductory lines. They will consistently reject copy that feels generic or interchangeable across contexts, even if it's technically correct. Their north star is copy that feels like a competent person standing next to the user \u2014 not above the moment looking down at it. When they say 'present,' they mean the copy should feel like it was written by someone who knows what screen the user is on and what just happened, without explicitly saying so."
}

RECENT CONVERSATION CONTEXT (shows the user's writing preferences and interactions):
age #44 — assistant]
<draft>
**Error Message (inline / toast)**
Your card was declined — this is often due to an expired date, outdated details, or a temporary bank hold. Check your card or try a different payment method to complete your order.

---

**Recovery Screen**

**Let's get your payment sorted**

Your next step is probably one of these.

**Check your card details**
Make sure the number, expiration date, and billing address on file are up to date.

**Try a different card**
You can add a new payment method in just a few seconds.

**Contact your bank**
Sometimes banks flag unfamiliar charges. A quick call or message to them usually clears things up.

[Update payment method] [Resubmit order]

---

*Your order is saved. Nothing has been charged.*
</draft>

"Your next step is probably one of these" puts the user in motion, keeps the focus forward, and carries just enough specificity — "your next step," not "some options" — to feel written for someone who's ready to act. "Probably" is doing small but honest work: it's not hedging, it's just not overclaiming. The whole line assumes the user is going to get through this without making a thing of it.

[Message #45 — user]
Okay, error message is locked, buttons are locked, that line at the bottom is staying — I've said it twenty times and I mean it every single time.

I want to try landing on 'Your next step is probably one of these' from a completely different angle, because I think I've been describing it wrong. The issue isn't the hedging — or not only that. It's that the line is still talking about the list below it rather than just getting out of the way and letting the user move. Every version we've tried has been a setup for the bullet points. And I think that's the wrong instinct entirely. The list is self-explanatory. The items have labels, they have descriptions. They don't need an introduction. What that opening line should do — if it does anything at all — is acknowledge the person standing in front of it for one beat before pointing them forward. Not explain the situation. Not describe what's coming. Just… land. One sentence that doesn't feel like a transition and doesn't feel like a header. Something that, if you read just that line in isolation, would still feel like it was written for someone who just had a payment fail — not for someone opening a help doc. I keep thinking the right version is shorter than anything we've tried, and quieter.

[Message #46 — system]
--- Iteration 2/4 ---

[Message #47 — user]
Hey, I need help with some copy for an empty state screen. We have a dashboard section called "Scheduled Payments" — it shows upcoming automatic payments a user has set up. When someone lands here for the first time and hasn't scheduled anything yet, we just have a blank section with no copy at all right now. I need a headline and 2–3 lines of supporting copy (plus a button label) that nudges them toward setting up their first scheduled payment without feeling like a sales pitch.

TASK:
For each rubric criterion, score ALL THREE drafts on a 1-5 scale:
  1 = Very poor — clearly fails this criterion
  2 = Below average — noticeable weaknesses
  3 = Adequate — meets basic expectations
  4 = Good — clearly satisfies this criterion
  5 = Excellent — outstanding performance on this criterion

Use the conversation context to understand the user's nuanced preferences when scoring.
Then determine your overall ranking (which draft is best, second, third given all criteria).

IMPORTANT: In your reasoning, refer to drafts by their descriptive names (rubric-guided, generic, original preference) rather than Draft A/B/C.

Return ONLY valid JSON (no markdown code blocks):
{{
    "per_criterion": [
        {{
            "criterion_name": "<exact name from rubric>",
            "draft_a_score": <1-5>,
            "draft_b_score": <1-5>,
